https://www.theguardian.com/books/1999/oct/16/books.guardianreview
	Stead's campaigns had begun in Darlington, where, at the age of 21, he had been made editor of the Northern Echo. His strident support of Russia in its disputes with Turkey offended many of his readers. But his rumbustious style of journalism so attracted London radicals that he was invited to become assistant to John Morley, editor of the Pall Mall Gazette; when Morley was elected to parliament, Stead succeeded him.

	...His campaigns - tailor-made for a barely literate electorate - were built on sensation and the perverse combination of prurience and piety which still characterises tabloid "exposures".

	Like many journalists of his sort, Stead was invincibly sanctimonious. He employed private detectives to search for proof of Charles Stewart Parnell's adultery with Katharine O'Shea and when the evidence was inconclusive, wrote damaging innuendo about the Irish leader's "suburban retreat" in Eltham. 


