	...Stead chose to tell only half the truth. In July 1885, the Pall Mall Gazette published the first instalment of its revelation. Under the headline "The maiden tribute of modern Babylon", he described not the contrived outrage which he had acted out but what he claimed was a real abduction and rape. The story was told in lurid language. "All was quiet and still. A few moments later the door opened and the purchaser entered. There was a brief silence and then a wild and piteous cry - not a loud shriek but a helpless startled scream like the bleat of a frightened lamb."

	Fashionable society was outraged - not by the discovery that vice was common in London, but by Stead's decision to expose it. 


