	...Released from prison, Stead was even more convinced of his duty to purify society in general and politics in particular. He was immediately presented with another - though less justified - opportunity for moral outrage. Charles Dilke, the rising star of the Liberal Party, had been cited as co-respondent in a divorce case. For weeks the Pall Mall Gazette published supporting rumours ranging from the co-respondent's "forwardness" towards Lady Randolph Churchill, to the allegation that he "had six intrigues going at once". But Stead's preoccupation with vice was soon overtaken by a new obsession. He had become a spiritualist and, after the death of his son, was convinced that Julia A Ames - an American journalist who had met him in London shortly before her death - was sending him messages in which she "described what life was like for Willie on the other side". She also warned him of impending disaster. 


