	In 1912 Stead was invited to join the maiden voyage of the Titanic. Shortly before he left he told a friend: "I shall die a violent death." Asked how he knew, he replied: "I cannot tell. But I have had a vision and I know it to be true."The disaster in which he died had been foreshadowed in an article which he had written for the Pall Mall Gazette 20 years before. It concluded: "This is exactly what might take place and will take place if liners are set free short of lifeboats." When the Titanic (only 1,178 boat spaces for 2,224 passengers) hit the iceberg, he made no attempt to save his own life. Instead, he took his death for granted. "He was at the forefront with the women and children, putting them into the boats." 


this is weird


	The warmest tribute was paid to Stead by the admiral of the fleet, "Jackie" Fisher - an unlikely admirer of a radical journalist. It was Captain Fisher who, back in 1884, had supplied Stead with the information on which the Pall Mall Gazette based its unjustified allegation that Britain was vulnerable to attack from the sea. "Leaks" - like investigation, revelation and interview - were essential to the new journalism. Stead demonstrated that the techniques can be used for both good purposes and bad. 


